    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-05-03T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-05-03T14:00:00-05:00" n="86"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d86">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51W89 U.S.S.R./44: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BWC1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-05-03T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 3, 1934—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>65. Your 71, May 2, 4 p.m. The answer to each of your three questions is in the
                    negative. I think you are correct in awaiting a move from
                        <persName>Litvinoff</persName>. My belief is that he is maneuvering to have
                    negotiations transferred to Washington. Please advise the moment
                        <persName>Litvinoff</persName> approaches you, if at all.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
